<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/BECA2763-0902-40AA-8DB2-836A5731CF58"><gtr:id>BECA2763-0902-40AA-8DB2-836A5731CF58</gtr:id><gtr:name>Brunel University</gtr:name><gtr:department>School of Social Sciences</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Brunel University</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Uxbridge</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Middlesex</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>UB8 3PH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/BECA2763-0902-40AA-8DB2-836A5731CF58"><gtr:id>BECA2763-0902-40AA-8DB2-836A5731CF58</gtr:id><gtr:name>Brunel University</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Brunel University</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Uxbridge</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Middlesex</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>UB8 3PH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/F25D7B6C-A445-4B11-A1AD-875B5AE1FF59"><gtr:id>F25D7B6C-A445-4B11-A1AD-875B5AE1FF59</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Matthew</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>David</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Rablen</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-192-27-0014"><gtr:id>4587E2B2-F785-4425-BA1E-0C070259660E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Reviewing the evidence on the promotion of well-being for reshaping policies and programmes towards neighbourhood management, governance and developme</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-192-27-0014</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Recent years have seen an increased focus on the impact policies have on how people think and feel about their lives, not only on material well-being and economic development. Local authorities have been given new powers to promote 'the economic, social, or environmental well-being of their area'. Effective use of these powers, however, requires an understanding of what is meant by 'well-being' and, as a consequence, how local authorities can address their responsibilities to promote well-being. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The placement aims to help develop the understanding and use of the promotion of well-being as a guiding principle behind local authority policy interventions. It will review the evidence on the promotion of well-being for reshaping policies and programmes towards neighbourhood management, governance and development and resident engagement. In particular, it will review a growing recent literature examining ways of defining and measuring well-being. Combining these insights with the perspectives of local authority professionals, the placement aims to yield practical steps for local authorities, (along with partners such as Primary Care Trusts and the Third Sector) to promote well-being. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The placement is sponsored by Brent Council and the academic partner is Dr. Matthew Rablen, an economist at Brunel University.&lt;/p>

